	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-630">
		<article id="comment-630" class="comment">

			<div class="avatar">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/d1a238d145c84496b01e7fd6e11d8d0d?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />			</div>

			<div class="comment-entry">

				<div class="comment-head">
					<cite class="fn">Shane</cite>					<a class="time" href="http://chrispacia.wordpress.com/2013/09/16/a-new-libertarian-constitution/comment-page-1/#comment-630"><time datetime="2014-06-23T14:31:27+00:00">
					June 23, 2014 at 2:31 PM					</time></a>
									</div><!-- .comment-head -->

				<div class="comment-content">
										<p>I like what you have done with Roderick Long&#8217;s work.  I do think you have gone a bit too far, or closer to Articles of Confederation than to a Constitution.  While I do not see a need for the authority to make laws; I am open to the idea that there may be such a need in the future.  If Citizenship and therefore compliance is voluntary, I foresee little harm.  With the ability to easily repeal any law, almost all potential harm would be removed.</p>
<p>Where I disagree with you and Long; is in the need for a Federal Judiciary.  Over the past century all most all of the degradation of the Constitution has come through the courts.  If there are no courts, then this route to subversion is eliminated.  In a real pinch, if something cannot be mediated or arbitrated, then a last resort could be an appeal to the Assembly (or Council) and a committee of 3, 5, 7, 11 or whatever could be assigned to settle the matter.  I am very Rothbardian in my views and think independent courts (Brehons) are the best route to justice.  Besides, one less branch of government means less government.</p>
<p>I also disagree with yours and Long&#8217;s failure to &#8220;provide and maintain a Navy&#8221;.  Failure to follow this directive of the Constitution almost cost us our nation twice.  Freedom is constantly threatened by those who are not free.  The freer a nation, the greater will be the threats from other nations and their statists to destroy that freedom.  Until all states are free, a free state will need vigilance and a very strong military to protect itself.</p>
<p>Lastly; why tax citizens at all?  I can understand requiring fees, or minute tariffs.  The Cantons provide members to the Assembly, why not just tax the Cantons?  The Cantons could then tax or not tax their members as they see fit.  This would also add a greater check upon government expansion since even the Cantons paying of taxes would be voluntary, but contingent upon their maintaining a seat in the Assembly.</p>
<p>You have obviously put a great deal of work and thought into this; and I appreciate your efforts.<br />
Thank you.</p>
				</div>

